He has been asked to take up his lyre again to sing the glory of the emperor and his step-sons, and he begins as usual with ‘denial vain and coy excuse! ‘ He will take his lyre‚ indeed, but it is at Venus' bidding‚ to renew under her compulsion the bitter-sweet themes which he hoped he had laid aside.' Ode 2 is to the same purport, though it carries us a little further by the end. ‘He is no swan of Pindaric song, such as is needed for 50 high a task. Some greater poet, Antonius himself, may sing of Augustus returning in triumph with the Sygambri at his chariot wheels, and of the people's joy. It may be, in the rapture of that happy day, even he too may find a voice and sing his best, and shout with the shouting people⁷ and make his humble offerings.'
